Dee-en-ess, turning names into addresses.

You do not connect to a bare numeric address; you connect to a name like example dot com. Dee-en-ess, the domain name system, is what turns that name into an address. The lookup follows an order. First the system checks a local file, the hosts file under slash e-t-c, which holds hardcoded name-to-address mappings and always wins if it has an entry. Then it consults the system resolver, usually systemd-resolved. That resolver in turn queries the configured dee-en-ess servers, perhaps your provider's, your company's, or a public one, and those servers walk the wider dee-en-ess hierarchy to find the answer.

The hosts file is a simple text file, one mapping per line: an address followed by one or more names. It is handy for overriding dee-en-ess during development, blocking sites, or giving local machines memorable names, and because it is checked first, it beats every other source. The resolver configuration historically lived in the resolv dot conf file under slash e-t-c, whose name-server lines list the dee-en-ess servers in priority order, and whose search line lists domains to append to short names. But on modern systemd systems that file is just a symlink to one managed automatically, so you should not edit it directly; instead you use the resolve-c-t-l command to view the configuration, run a query, or set a server, and you make permanent changes through network-manager or the resolved configuration file.

For testing dee-en-ess directly, without trusting the local cache, the key tool is dig. You can dig a name to see the full answer, or, very usefully, dig at a specific server like one of the public ones to bypass your own resolver entirely. That last trick is the heart of dee-en-ess troubleshooting: if a query against a public server works but your normal lookup fails, you know the problem is your own resolver rather than the wider internet. There are also simpler front-ends, n-s-lookup and host, for quick checks.
